President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has questioned whether participation will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The referendum paper asked the following question: "Is it in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claim that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies such as the EU and NATO.
"Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all," said 79-year-old Olivera Georgievska in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote for it to be decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that no irregularities had been notified at 1 p.m.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% of the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters cast their vote.
“I’ve come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who was voting in Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dusko cast their vote in the Macedonian referendum on a name change that would open the way for NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
