“We are in favour of entering NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with our heads up, not by the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev said that accession to NATO would contribute to the investment that Macedonia so much needs, whose unemployment rate is more than 20%.
“I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80 percent of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
He said a positive result would be a “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Institute of Policy Research stated that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, which is less than the required participation.
