Throughout Bolivia, a land without seas, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the desire to resettle the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the greatest in decades, as Bolivia awaits an International Court of Justice resolution by October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the drive, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the International Court of Justice's ruling on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will decide in favour of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has the obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
