John Edward: Language Skills are Fundamental for the Citizens of the World
Scottish independent educational centres have a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in exams that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is noted that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can note that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest approval rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest score.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that form part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students received an A in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as the subjects of CTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of employers’ reasons for difficulties in filling jobs were attributed to a lack of linguistic skills.
Therefore, linguistic skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities requiring languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will enable that person to automatically advance to the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation. Also, it was established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they speak several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better chances of finding a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools will always be able to choose from several languages taught by teachers specializing in this subject.
Scotland’s independent educational centres devote all their efforts to provide a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages still have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competents for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
