North Korea says “there is no possibility” that they will disarm first unilaterally if they have no confidence
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened his distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility for his country to unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho stated before the annual General Assembly of the international body that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we have not received any similar response from the United States," he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances, there is no possibility that we disarm ourselves unilaterally first.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phase-by-phase” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as it did not without further a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work in favor of the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang should give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose coercively, even by objecting to a declaration of end of war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced at a bomb and plateau by the U.S. leader before the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea’s leader, over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea had been the party involved in denuclearization rather than the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in a slump.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward U.S. soil after “malicious President” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim “a rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that it was necessary to continue applying sanctions until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no set deadline for this: “We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its advances.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we make final and fully verified denuclearization a reality.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying there had been advances, but a few hours later, North Korea denounced that its “requirements were those of a mafia.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "corresponding measures".
He said Kim had informed him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take a Course on How to Rest Enough
Thanks to a new course that is being taught at Harvard University this year, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
A professor discovered that the world’s number one university students often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
Their motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl approached me and asked me why she just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of dreaming, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of setting up a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of students right away.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” Professor Czeisler added.
He stated that the culture of pride for “sleeping the night” still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure that students are subjected to meant sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the year before during his first year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
Expect that the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is for students to think about putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by the displays of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so that they end up having problems.
